00:00:00.415 --> 00:00:01.765
- [Voiceover] I'm here with Emily,

00:00:01.765 --> 00:00:03.248
our biology content fellow,

00:00:03.248 --> 00:00:05.099
to talk about PCR,

00:00:05.099 --> 00:00:07.410
or Polymerase Chain Reaction,

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:08.682
which you've actually done a lot of.

00:00:08.682 --> 00:00:10.494
Why have you done PCR?

00:00:10.494 --> 00:00:12.925
- [Voiceover] PCR was kind of the mainstay

00:00:12.925 --> 00:00:15.343
of my graduate project,

00:00:15.343 --> 00:00:17.262
where I built all sorts

00:00:17.262 --> 00:00:19.686
of different recombinant DNA molecules,

00:00:19.686 --> 00:00:21.901
and used them to learn
things about plants.

00:00:21.901 --> 00:00:24.569
- [Voiceover] And so what
does PCR in particular do?

00:00:24.569 --> 00:00:27.025
- [Voiceover] PCR basically
makes you a lot of copies

00:00:27.025 --> 00:00:30.241
of a particular fragment of
DNA that you're interested in.

00:00:30.241 --> 00:00:32.609
- [Voiceover] And so how does that...

00:00:32.609 --> 00:00:34.066
Why would you need to make a lot of copies

00:00:34.066 --> 00:00:36.201
of a particular fragment of DNA?

00:00:36.201 --> 00:00:39.438
- [Voiceover] So you might want
to be making lots of copies

00:00:39.438 --> 00:00:41.725
so that you can clone it into a plasmid,

00:00:41.725 --> 00:00:43.469
and then do some other
experiments with it,

00:00:43.469 --> 00:00:44.795
that's a big use.

00:00:44.795 --> 00:00:46.044
- [Voiceover] So when
we talked about cloning,

00:00:46.044 --> 00:00:47.158
and we're talking about sticking

00:00:47.158 --> 00:00:49.099
a fragment of DNA inside of a plasmid,

00:00:49.099 --> 00:00:51.430
it's not like you're just
sticking one fragment

00:00:51.430 --> 00:00:52.692
into one plasmid,

00:00:52.692 --> 00:00:54.274
you're doing that with many,

00:00:54.274 --> 00:00:55.951
so you need a lot of fragments of DNA.

00:00:55.951 --> 00:00:58.082
- [Voiceover] Exactly. That is exactly it.

00:00:58.082 --> 00:00:59.390
- [Voiceover] And you might start

00:00:59.390 --> 00:01:01.733
with a very small sample of DNA.

00:01:01.733 --> 00:01:05.164
Where else would you have to do PCR?

00:01:05.164 --> 00:01:08.064
- [Voiceover] PCR is
used a lot in forensics,

00:01:08.064 --> 00:01:10.552
it's also used a lot
in medical diagnostics,

00:01:10.552 --> 00:01:12.704
so this could actually be your DNA

00:01:12.704 --> 00:01:15.913
that was being checked
to see if you have a gene

00:01:15.913 --> 00:01:18.330
that would predispose you
to a particular condition,

00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:20.754
all sorts of really
practical applications.

00:01:20.754 --> 00:01:22.627
- [Voiceover] Because
it's hard to identify

00:01:22.627 --> 00:01:25.541
just one fragment of that gene.

00:01:25.541 --> 00:01:27.555
So you want to make copies,

00:01:27.555 --> 00:01:29.349
or as they say amplify it,

00:01:29.349 --> 00:01:31.034
so that you could run it in gels and stuff

00:01:31.034 --> 00:01:32.556
and see how all of those molecules,

00:01:32.556 --> 00:01:34.291
how big they are or something like that.

00:01:34.291 --> 00:01:35.828
- [Voiceover] Exactly,
if you were just looking

00:01:35.828 --> 00:01:38.146
in your DNA pulled out of your cell,

00:01:38.146 --> 00:01:39.802
that would be a needle in a haystack.

00:01:39.802 --> 00:01:41.762
So this is how you can really zoom in

00:01:41.762 --> 00:01:43.641
and look at just the
thing you need to see.

00:01:43.641 --> 00:01:44.610
- [Voiceover] Okay.

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:46.153
So, you've drawn some diagrams here,

00:01:46.153 --> 00:01:48.245
and I actually have never done PCR,

00:01:48.245 --> 00:01:49.139
but you have,

00:01:49.139 --> 00:01:51.452
so I'm going to tell you how
I understand it happening,

00:01:51.452 --> 00:01:53.993
and then you tell me if this makes sense.

