So, what you drew over here,

00:01:56.738 --> 00:01:58.997
this is double-stranded DNA,

00:01:58.997 --> 00:02:02.405
and this could have been from
a sample of someone's hair,

00:02:02.405 --> 00:02:04.452
or whatever else,

00:02:04.452 --> 00:02:07.318
and let's say we want to replicate

00:02:07.318 --> 00:02:10.839
or make many, many copies
of a fragment of this.

00:02:10.839 --> 00:02:13.226
So let's say the fragment
that we really care about

00:02:13.226 --> 00:02:16.731
is the fragment roughly from there,

00:02:16.731 --> 00:02:17.600
to...

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:19.014
There.

00:02:19.014 --> 00:02:23.149
This part is what we want
to make multiple copies of.

00:02:23.149 --> 00:02:25.068
And so this first step,

00:02:25.068 --> 00:02:27.076
denaturation...

00:02:27.076 --> 00:02:29.941
I have trouble pronouncing things.

00:02:29.941 --> 00:02:30.774
- [Voiceover] It's a weird word.

00:02:30.774 --> 00:02:32.384
- [Voiceover] It's a weird word.

