00:05:49.658 --> 00:05:51.463
where you heat it up,

00:05:51.463 --> 00:05:53.434
the strands separate,

00:05:53.434 --> 00:05:56.780
then you have all of
this extra primer there.

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:59.002
Because there's so much primer,

00:05:59.002 --> 00:06:02.138
the primer is much more likely to bind to,

00:06:02.138 --> 00:06:04.019
at least at this part of the sequence,

00:06:04.019 --> 00:06:05.994
then for these two strands
to get back together

00:06:05.994 --> 00:06:07.178
at this point,

00:06:07.178 --> 00:06:09.306
and then you have the polymerase,

00:06:09.306 --> 00:06:11.083
the taq polymerase in particular,

00:06:11.083 --> 00:06:12.808
and you would have added
that at the beginning,

00:06:12.808 --> 00:06:14.044
the taq polymerase,

00:06:14.044 --> 00:06:17.267
I guess I'll put it in a yellow color.

00:06:17.267 --> 00:06:21.016
So you would also put all
that taq polymerase in there.

00:06:21.016 --> 00:06:23.731
And once again, these
things aren't robots,

00:06:23.731 --> 00:06:25.096
they don't know exactly
what they need to do,

00:06:25.096 --> 00:06:26.576
they just bump into
things in the right way

00:06:26.576 --> 00:06:27.944
and react in the right way,

00:06:27.944 --> 00:06:29.195
and then you would also have to add

00:06:29.195 --> 00:06:30.176
a bunch of nucleotides.

00:06:30.176 --> 00:06:31.266
- [Voiceover] Yes, absolutely.

00:06:31.266 --> 00:06:32.673
Your reaction is not going to work

00:06:32.673 --> 00:06:34.587
if you forget the nucleotides.

00:06:34.587 --> 00:06:36.573
- [Voiceover] So, the taq polymerase,

00:06:36.573 --> 00:06:38.722
when you heat it back up again

00:06:38.722 --> 00:06:40.728
