00:07:26.371 --> 00:07:27.553
in two ways,

00:07:27.553 --> 00:07:30.217
and one is that's sort of
what the polymerase does,

00:07:30.217 --> 00:07:32.513
is you know, add things to make a chain,

00:07:32.513 --> 00:07:35.204
but there's actually even
more of a chain reaction

00:07:35.204 --> 00:07:36.432
to mention here,

00:07:36.432 --> 00:07:38.608
and that's that we're actually getting

00:07:38.608 --> 00:07:41.525
this kind of exponential process going on.

00:07:41.525 --> 00:07:43.200
- [Voiceover] So you do it one cycle,

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:44.658
you get to this situation right here,

00:07:44.658 --> 00:07:46.353
you heat it up, the strands separate,

00:07:46.353 --> 00:07:48.553
you cool it down, the primers attach,

00:07:48.553 --> 00:07:52.625
you heat it up again, the
taq polymerase does its job,

00:07:52.625 --> 00:07:54.016
and like all polymerase,

00:07:54.016 --> 00:07:56.289
it goes from the 5 prime
to the 3 prime direction,

00:07:56.289 --> 00:07:58.066
we talked about that in the application.

00:07:58.066 --> 00:07:58.899
- [Voiceover] Precisely.

00:07:58.899 --> 00:08:00.277
- [Voiceover] So now you have two strands,

00:08:00.277 --> 00:08:01.834
but now, since all of that
stuff is in that solution,

00:08:01.834 --> 00:08:03.822
you can heat it up again,

00:08:03.822 --> 00:08:07.396
now these two strands can turn into...

00:08:07.396 --> 00:08:10.367
Or these two double strands can now

00:08:10.367 --> 00:08:12.715
turn into four single strands,

00:08:12.715 --> 00:08:14.949
then you can cool it down again.

00:08:14.949 --> 00:08:17.055
Now, they get primers attached to them,

00:08:17.055 --> 00:08:18.308
and they're still the same primer,

00:08:18.308 --> 00:08:20.836
because we still care
about the same sequence.

00:08:20.836 --> 00:08:24.157
And so now you go from one to two to four,

00:08:24.157 --> 00:08:25.980
